{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_7","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc 'cat .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/pageflows-research.md'","aggregated_output":"# PageFlows Research\n\nGenerated during active Fabro babysitting because the research fanout produced usable reference-pack data but did not materialize this exact required filename. This file is source-limited, contains no secrets, and should be superseded by richer agent research in future workflow runs.\n\n## Source List\n- page flows (https://pageflows.com/)\n- page flows (https://pageflows.com/)\n- page flows (https://pageflows.com/)\n- page flows (https://pageflows.com/)\n\n## References\n### Reference 1: pageflows\n- Category: pattern_library\n- Provider/source: page flows\n- URL: https://pageflows.com/\n- Screen type: onboarding\n- Tags: page flows, setup, progressive_disclosure\n- What to adapt: Apply progressive setup: confirm task intent first, then optional strictness, then mission details.\n- What not to copy: Do not mirror any proprietary screen arrangement from uncaptured references.\n\n### Reference 2: pageflows\n- Category: pattern_library\n- Provider/source: page flows\n- URL: https://pageflows.com/\n- Screen type: active_task\n- Tags: page flows, urgent_wake, single_action\n- What to adapt: Use one primary wake action and stable progress markers in urgent mode.\n- What not to copy: Do not introduce choice overload when mission is active.\n\n### Reference 3: pageflows\n- Category: pattern_library\n- Provider/source: page flows\n- URL: https://pageflows.com/\n- Screen type: completion\n- Tags: page flows, calm_mode, recovery\n- What to adapt: Preserve completion confirmation then offer a calm retry/recover path with context.\n- What not to copy: Do not escalate to punitive lockout or repeated alarmed error messaging.\n\n### Reference 4: pageflows\n- Category: pattern_library\n- Provider/source: page flows\n- URL: https://pageflows.com/\n- Screen type: history_streaks\n- Tags: page flows, accountability, history\n- What to adapt: Keep history readable with explicit definitions for missed days and repair actions.\n- What not to copy: Do not duplicate exact habit badges, streak rewards, or gamified pressure without safety checks.\n\n## Cross-Cutting Observations\n### Observation 1\n- What to adapt: Add explicit progress hints during first-run and a skip-safe path with safe defaults.\n- What not to copy: Do not force a strict linear sequence without recovery context.\n\n### Observation 2\n- What to adapt: Delay visual polish decisions that require pixel verification until screenshots are captured.\n- What not to copy: Do not claim validated visual quality where no evidence capture exists.\n\n### Observation 3\n- What to adapt: Add explicit fallback evidence tiering and mark inference-backed suggestions clearly in design docs.\n- What not to copy: Do not use invented competitor or review claims as if they were validated findings.\n\n### Observation 4\n- What to adapt: Strengthen wake-state surface for visible next step and state completion clarity.\n- What not to copy: Do not add hidden timers or non-explicit transitions in active wake mode.\n\n### Observation 5\n- What to adapt: Separate operational and accountability surfaces clearly in profile and home.\n- What not to copy: Do not keep critical wake controls mixed with legal/help actions.\n\n### Observation 6\n- What to adapt: Prioritize design changes with strong evidence in-app and defer uncertain behavior claims.\n- What not to copy: Do not overfit to unavailable external claims or unverified competitor patterns.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_5","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc 'cat .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/app-store-review-mining.md'","aggregated_output":"# App Store Review Mining\n\nGenerated during active Fabro babysitting because the research fanout produced usable reference-pack data but did not materialize this exact required filename. This file is source-limited, contains no secrets, and should be superseded by richer agent research in future workflow runs.\n\n## Source List\n- app_store\n- app_store\n\n## References\n### Reference 1: app_store\n- Category: review_mining\n- Provider/source: app_store\n- Screen type: home\n- Tags: evidence_gap, app_store\n- What to adapt: Treat retention and pain themes as hypotheses and delay feature-level commitments until review evidence is captured.\n- What not to copy: Do not infer explicit negative/positive App Store themes without review corpus.\n\n### Reference 2: app_store\n- Category: review_mining\n- Provider/source: app_store\n- Screen type: onboarding\n- Tags: evidence_gap, onboarding\n- What to adapt: Use onboarding copy that reduces drop-off with safe defaults and optional skip.\n- What not to copy: Do not ship high-friction onboarding assumptions based on absent retention evidence.\n\n## Cross-Cutting Observations\n### Observation 1\n- What to adapt: Add explicit progress hints during first-run and a skip-safe path with safe defaults.\n- What not to copy: Do not force a strict linear sequence without recovery context.\n\n### Observation 2\n- What to adapt: Delay visual polish decisions that require pixel verification until screenshots are captured.\n- What not to copy: Do not claim validated visual quality where no evidence capture exists.\n\n### Observation 3\n- What to adapt: Add explicit fallback evidence tiering and mark inference-backed suggestions clearly in design docs.\n- What not to copy: Do not use invented competitor or review claims as if they were validated findings.\n\n### Observation 4\n- What to adapt: Strengthen wake-state surface for visible next step and state completion clarity.\n- What not to copy: Do not add hidden timers or non-explicit transitions in active wake mode.\n\n### Observation 5\n- What to adapt: Separate operational and accountability surfaces clearly in profile and home.\n- What not to copy: Do not keep critical wake controls mixed with legal/help actions.\n\n### Observation 6\n- What to adapt: Prioritize design changes with strong evidence in-app and defer uncertain behavior claims.\n- What not to copy: Do not overfit to unavailable external claims or unverified competitor patterns.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_4","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc 'cat .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/competitor-flows.md'","aggregated_output":"# Competitor Flow Research\n\nGenerated during active Fabro babysitting because the research fanout produced usable reference-pack data but did not materialize this exact required filename. This file is source-limited, contains no secrets, and should be superseded by richer agent research in future workflow runs.\n\n## Source List\n- competitor\n- competitor\n- competitor\n- competitor\n\n## References\n### Reference 1: competitor\n- Category: competitor_flow\n- Provider/source: competitor\n- Screen type: onboarding\n- Tags: competitor, onboarding, sequence\n- What to adapt: Preserve deterministic onboarding sequencing but make it explicit and cancellable with a soft default path for first-run uncertainty.\n- What not to copy: Do not hard-lock users behind rigid first-run steps before they understand core value.\n\n### Reference 2: competitor\n- Category: competitor_flow\n- Provider/source: competitor\n- Screen type: home\n- Tags: competitor, navigation, tabs\n- What to adapt: Keep a predictable tab model and strengthen labels to reduce ambiguity between task status and support/account lanes.\n- What not to copy: Do not over-conflate settings/support actions with core wake execution actions.\n\n### Reference 3: competitor\n- Category: competitor_flow\n- Provider/source: competitor\n- Screen type: active_task\n- Tags: competitor, urgent_mode, mission_progress\n- What to adapt: Prioritize explicit active-task controls and immediate progress indication once a mission starts.\n- What not to copy: Do not overload the active screen with secondary decision links during wake mode.\n\n### Reference 4: competitor\n- Category: competitor_flow\n- Provider/source: competitor\n- Screen type: profile_settings\n- Tags: competitor, profile, settings\n- What to adapt: Use account/support sectioning with calmer hierarchy and clearer action grouping.\n- What not to copy: Do not keep operational and high-risk actions at the same visual weight or proximity.\n\n## Cross-Cutting Observations\n### Observation 1\n- What to adapt: Add explicit progress hints during first-run and a skip-safe path with safe defaults.\n- What not to copy: Do not force a strict linear sequence without recovery context.\n\n### Observation 2\n- What to adapt: Delay visual polish decisions that require pixel verification until screenshots are captured.\n- What not to copy: Do not claim validated visual quality where no evidence capture exists.\n\n### Observation 3\n- What to adapt: Add explicit fallback evidence tiering and mark inference-backed suggestions clearly in design docs.\n- What not to copy: Do not use invented competitor or review claims as if they were validated findings.\n\n### Observation 4\n- What to adapt: Strengthen wake-state surface for visible next step and state completion clarity.\n- What not to copy: Do not add hidden timers or non-explicit transitions in active wake mode.\n\n### Observation 5\n- What to adapt: Separate operational and accountability surfaces clearly in profile and home.\n- What not to copy: Do not keep critical wake controls mixed with legal/help actions.\n\n### Observation 6\n- What to adapt: Prioritize design changes with strong evidence in-app and defer uncertain behavior claims.\n- What not to copy: Do not overfit to unavailable external claims or unverified competitor patterns.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_9","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc 'cat .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/behavioral-ux-research.md'","aggregated_output":"# Behavioral UX Research\n\nGenerated during active Fabro babysitting because the research fanout produced usable reference-pack data but did not materialize this exact required filename. This file is source-limited, contains no secrets, and should be superseded by richer agent research in future workflow runs.\n\n## Source List\n- behavioral_research\n\n## References\n### Reference 1: behavioral_research\n- Category: behavioral_ux\n- Provider/source: behavioral_research\n- Screen type: completion\n- Tags: behavioral, calm_setup, urgent_wake\n- What to adapt: Differentiate low-pressure setup interactions from high-pressure wake execution interactions by changing density and copy tone.\n- What not to copy: Do not use shame-driven reminders or anxiety-heavy framing in recovery.\n\n## Cross-Cutting Observations\n### Observation 1\n- What to adapt: Add explicit progress hints during first-run and a skip-safe path with safe defaults.\n- What not to copy: Do not force a strict linear sequence without recovery context.\n\n### Observation 2\n- What to adapt: Delay visual polish decisions that require pixel verification until screenshots are captured.\n- What not to copy: Do not claim validated visual quality where no evidence capture exists.\n\n### Observation 3\n- What to adapt: Add explicit fallback evidence tiering and mark inference-backed suggestions clearly in design docs.\n- What not to copy: Do not use invented competitor or review claims as if they were validated findings.\n\n### Observation 4\n- What to adapt: Strengthen wake-state surface for visible next step and state completion clarity.\n- What not to copy: Do not add hidden timers or non-explicit transitions in active wake mode.\n\n### Observation 5\n- What to adapt: Separate operational and accountability surfaces clearly in profile and home.\n- What not to copy: Do not keep critical wake controls mixed with legal/help actions.\n\n### Observation 6\n- What to adapt: Prioritize design changes with strong evidence in-app and defer uncertain behavior claims.\n- What not to copy: Do not overfit to unavailable external claims or unverified competitor patterns.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_6","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc 'cat .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md'","aggregated_output":"# Mobbin MCP Research\n\n## Source Policy\n\n- Prefer official Mobbin MCP evidence when a consumable artifact is available.\n- In this run, Mobbin preflight/checks passed, but no consumable Mobbin markdown artifact was materialized for downstream synthesis.\n- Fallback to non-Mobbin pattern references is allowed only for interaction principles.\n- Do not copy proprietary screenshots, exact layouts, UI copy, brand identity, or assets.\n- Do not print secrets, credentials, tokens, cookies, private keys, session values, or environment values.\n- Any fallback patterns referenced for this stage are private-only evidence.\n\n## Source List\n\n1. Preflight/availability evidence: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json`\n2. Baseline run output context: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/codex/mobbin-mcp-research.last-message.md` (if present)\n3. Research gap marker: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json`\n4. Publicly-inspired wake/task UX sequence principles from prior stage requirements.\n\n## Access Path Used\n\nOfficial Mobbin MCP path was configured in the run environment but no direct Mobbin artifact was produced for this branch handoff. This file is a source-limited fallback to keep the pipeline moving without inventing private layouts.\n\n## Pattern References\n\n### Reference 1: Calm Setup Sequence\n\n- Source path: fallback source-limited sequence notes\n- Screen type: onboarding\n- Pattern summary: Setup should progress in bounded steps and keep defaults reversible at first use.\n- what_to_adapt: Keep onboarding modular and avoid forcing strict settings before a user has created at least one wake attempt.\n- what_not_to_copy: Avoid exact reproduction of competitor onboarding copy, iconography, or structure.\n\n### Reference 2: Single-Path Urgent Wake Execution\n\n- Source path: fallback source-limited sequence notes\n- Screen type: active_task\n- Pattern summary: The mission screen should center one primary wake action with clear next-state messaging.\n- what_to_adapt: Prioritize one urgent action and explicit completion status.\n- what_not_to_copy: Do not replicate proprietary task layout or coercive escalation timing.\n\n### Reference 3: Recovery Without Shame\n\n- Source path: fallback source-limited sequence notes\n- Screen type: completion\n- Pattern summary: Miss/retry states should preserve trust and provide a clear reset path.\n- what_to_adapt: Use restorative copy and an immediate low-friction retry/recovery CTA.\n- what_not_to_copy: Do not use public-availability-dependent claims or shame-oriented recovery phrasing.\n\n### Reference 4: Streak and Reliability Clarity\n\n- Source path: fallback source-limited sequence notes\n- Screen type: history_streaks\n- Pattern summary: Reliability context should show why streaks change and how to repair a missed day.\n- what_to_adapt: Keep history readable and actionable over purely decorative reward counters.\n- what_not_to_copy: Do not copy proprietary badge visuals or exact reward logic.\n\n## Screen Type Coverage\n\n- onboarding\n- active_task\n- completion\n- history_streaks\n\n## Raw Asset Privacy\n\n- path: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md`\n  - source: mobbin_fallback\n  - private_only: true\n\n## what_to_adapt\n\n- Use calm-mode first-run sequencing, urgent-mode focused execution, and recovery-first post-miss language.\n- Preserve mental model continuity between setup, active wake, and accountability loops.\n- Keep interaction pattern principles but generate original screen implementations.\n\n## what_not_to_copy\n\n- Do not copy exact Mobbin layouts, visuals, copy, or brand patterns.\n- Do not use unavailable private evidence as if it were fully verified.\n- Do not implement punitive or panic-driven wake mechanics that reduce safety.\n\n## Fallback Notes\n\n- This artifact exists because Mobbin outputs were not present in downstream output despite stage success markers.\n- Re-run the Mobbin stage with guaranteed artifact write-through when a high-fidelity pattern comparison is required.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
