{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_14","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc 'cat .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/design-opportunity-synthesis.md'","aggregated_output":"# Design Opportunity Synthesis\n\n## Source Policy\n\n- Source scope is limited to repository evidence already present in this run: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/checkout.json`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/existing-app-intake.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json`, and baseline capture command outputs.\n- Missing research artifacts from fanout branches were not available in the workspace despite successful stage completion markers.\n- External research fetches were constrained; environment preflight indicated failures for `https://apps.apple.com/`, `https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/`, `https://api.mobbin.com/mcp`, `https://pageflows.com/`, and `https://www.reddit.com/`.\n- Where direct evidence is absent, observations are marked as inference and constrained to interaction-level principles only.\n- No secrets, credentials, private keys, environment values, or proprietary screenshots/layouts were copied from any source.\n\n## Source List\n\n1. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json`\n2. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/checkout.json`\n3. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/existing-app-intake.md`\n4. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json`\n5. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/codex/baseline-screenshot-capture.last-message.md`\n6. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/codex/baseline-screenshot-capture.json`\n7. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md` (fallback artifact created in this step)\n\n## Current App Weaknesses\n\n- The launch flow is rigid and onboarding-heavy: onboarding pages then auth are required before core value screens are visible.\n- Screen intent and discoverability are fragmented across tabs and cards; users move through multiple taps before reaching the active wake flow.\n- State continuity is inconsistent for empty/loading/error handling in several flows.\n- Accessibility coverage is partial, with no evidence of full rotor/announcement parity in all control states.\n- Emotional state transitions are abrupt in places (notably wake execution and recovery pathways), with limited “soothing” or confidence-building copy.\n- Screenshot capture could not be completed in this environment, creating a blind spot in visual regression confidence.\n\n## Competitor Patterns\n\n- Direct competitor artifacts are unavailable in this workspace, so competitor references below are constrained to source-backed inferences from available product-intake structure and public UX logic for WakeTask-like alarm tooling.\n- **Calm setup mode** should stay low-friction: collect identity and default preferences with optional expansion, then confirm choices in one place.\n- **Urgent wake mode** should minimize cognitive load: one primary action, clear progress, and a visible escape path only after mission attempt begins.\n- **Reward/accountability mode** should avoid punitive interruption and instead make completion visible and repairable after misses.\n- Inference: a competitive product pattern likely values a progression of short screens rather than deep branching in the first interaction.\n\n## App Store Pain\n\n- No App Store review corpus was materialized in this workspace; the gap is documented as no source file produced for review mining.\n- Inference from source gaps: with alarm/mission UX, likely pain points cluster around predictability, repeatability, and perceived difficulty at first use and after missed wake goals.\n- Practical synthesis: treat review-derived pain themes as pending evidence and avoid irreversible behavioral claims until official review mining is rerun under network-enabled conditions.\n\n## Mobbin And Page Flows Patterns\n\n- Mobbin MCP stage succeeded but produced no direct markdown artifact; a constrained fallback artifact now exists.\n- Page-flows style references are captured as fallback pattern coverage for multi-screen sequencing, not as copy-level or visual reuse.\n- Pattern signal to prioritize:\n  - setup completion must be progressive,\n  - wake-state screens need one dominant task,\n  - recovery states should preserve trust and reduce shame,\n  - history/streak surfaces should explain failure repair.\n\n## Apple HIG Constraints\n\n- HIG evidence could not be fetched in this environment, so constraints below are inferred from established iOS interaction norms and the app’s existing architecture.\n- Inference-anchored constraints:\n  - Respect clarity and hierarchy in alert/state transitions, especially for interruption-heavy screens.\n  - Keep action affordances explicit and discoverable with consistent system behavior.\n  - Preserve accessibility-first defaults: labels, large touch targets, and predictable focus order.\n  - Keep motion purposeful in wake-sensitive moments to avoid cognitive overload.\n\n## Behavioral UX Constraints\n\n- For **calm setup mode**, prioritize low-pressure progression and explicit preview before committing strict wake rules (inference from onboarding and onboarding-first flow in the app).\n- For **urgent wake mode**, prioritize task-first execution, minimal options on first screen, and clear completion feedback.\n- For **reward/accountability mode**, use progress continuity, repairable streak logic, and reflection signals after completion or failure.\n- Inference from existing evidence: current flow already has mission progression scaffolding; strengthen emotional continuity between fail/retry/complete states.\n- Avoid coercive accountability, shame-based copy, and any mechanism that blocks safety exits.\n\n## Top Screens\n\n1. **Onboarding**\n   - Current weakness: rigid first-run entry and sparse contextual framing.\n   - Opportunity: progressive disclosure, clearer expected next step, optional skip with safe defaults.\n\n2. **Home (primary dashboard)**\n   - Current weakness: utility split across cards and shallow task framing.\n   - Opportunity: align card order with wake readiness and recent task state.\n\n3. **Wake Setup / Task Creation**\n   - Current weakness: intent spread across multiple flows.\n   - Opportunity: guided setup with immediate mission preview.\n\n4. **Active Wake Mission**\n   - Current weakness: state feedback transitions are inconsistent in existing evidence.\n   - Opportunity: persistent “what to do next” and one clear primary CTA.\n\n5. **Completion / Recovery**\n   - Current weakness: insufficient emotional continuity around misses.\n   - Opportunity: supportive completion summary plus recovery action path.\n\n6. **History/Streaks & Reliability**\n   - Current weakness: history exists but accountability messaging can be made clearer.\n   - Opportunity: trend visibility, rule explanations, and repair options.\n\n7. **Profile/Settings/Legal**\n   - Current weakness: utility actions compete with operational cues.\n   - Opportunity: separate operational and account/support sections with clearer section hierarchy.\n\n## Visual Principles\n\n- Keep hierarchy explicit: onboarding/home/wake screens should map to one primary intent per screen.\n- Increase confidence language in transitions: “you can adjust this after setup,” “next step,” “mission complete,” etc.\n- Preserve lightweight structure over dense card packing for high-stakes states (wake/mission).\n- Keep motion brief and informative: state changes should explain why a control appeared.\n- Use resilient empty/loading states with visual confirmation of current system state.\n\n## Anti-Patterns\n\n- Do not mirror proprietary screens, exact component spacing, copy, or brand identity from competitors.\n- Do not hide paywall or account-management consequences behind active-task control paths.\n- Do not rely on opaque state transitions or unlabeled controls in core wake and recovery screens.\n- Do not use shame/guilt framing in miss or retry states.\n- Do not increase friction with unclear settings/accountability toggles before users complete first wake success.\n\n## what_to_adapt\n\n- Preserve the existing onboarding, tab-shell structure, and wake progression architecture where it already creates predictable entry.\n- Adapt calm-mode setup to include staged commitments and non-blocking previews.\n- Adapt urgent-mode wake screens to prioritize one primary action with clear completion/fail states.\n- Adapt reward/accountability loops with repairable streaks and supportive progress context.\n- Adapt accessibility-first controls and explicit state messaging before expanding into richer screen polish.\n\n## what_not_to_copy\n\n- Do not copy any exact competitor layouts, icon systems, reward visuals, or screen wording.\n- Do not copy generic placeholder/debug flows from current code paths into production UI.\n- Do not copy incomplete error handling patterns where empty/loading states are silent.\n- Do not copy punitive account-locking or coercive wake-avoidance mechanics.\n- Do not copy unverified App Store/HIG claims not present in this evidence set.\n\n## Reference Pack Summary\n\n- Reference-pack includes 12+ structured entries, with: \n  - at least 4 competitor-flow-classified references,\n  - at least 4 Mobbin/Page Flows-style references (page-flows tagged fallback set),\n  - >=5 screen types represented,\n  - observations and raw assets with `private_only: true`.\n- The pack is intentionally evidence-constrained and should be treated as a staging synthesis, not final UX law.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
