{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_16","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"cat > .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/design-opportunity-synthesis.md <<'EOF'\n# Design Opportunity Synthesis\n\n## Source Policy\n- Source policy: only local research and app evidence in this branch were used.\n- Allowed evidence includes: \"'`.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/checkout.json`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/codex/baseline-screenshot-capture.json`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/existing-app-intake.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/competitor-flows.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/app-store-review-mining.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/pageflows-research.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/apple-hig-research.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/behavioral-ux-research.md`.\n- I did not include proprietary visuals, exact competitor layouts, screenshot assets, brand copy, credentials, or secrets.\n- Where evidence is indirect (for example inferred behavioral intent from fallback material), I marked it as inference in the synthesis text.\n\n## Source List\n1. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/existing-app-intake.md`\n2. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json`\n3. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/competitor-flows.md`\n4. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/app-store-review-mining.md`\n5. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md`\n6. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/pageflows-research.md`\n7. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/apple-hig-research.md`\n8. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/behavioral-ux-research.md`\n9. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/checkout.json`\n10. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/codex/baseline-screenshot-capture.json`\n11. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json`\n\n## Current App Weaknesses\n- Onboarding and auth are tightly sequenced before reaching mission value, as documented in intake flow evidence, which can increase first-run drop-off without a clearly cancellable or paused path.\n- Tab intent is under-labeled for mission flow clarity; existing intake records Home/Runs/Profile structure but does not show visible evidence that users can infer urgency state from Home.\n- Wake and completion flow states are present, but state transition confidence appears uneven across loading/empty/error conditions, creating ambiguity in urgency moments.\n- Profile mixes operational actions (help/legal/account controls) with mission-support actions, weakening the separation between “wake execution” and “account management” goals.\n- No validated PNG captures or screenshot manifest were produced in this environment due missing iOS simulator tooling (`xcrun` unavailable), so visual regressions for top screens are unsupported.\n- Inference: accessibility coverage is present in some controls, but intake notes indicate incomplete coverage across profile/dashboard action states.\n\n## Competitor Patterns\n- Calm setup mode: competitor-flow references indicate progression is strongest when setup is staged and reversible; this aligns with reducing first-run friction and avoiding irreversible gates.\n- Urgent wake mode: references emphasize a single primary action during active sessions; avoid overloading users with secondary decisions at the wake moment.\n- Reward/accountability mode: competitor cues favor visible completion continuity and repair paths rather than punitive enforcement.\n- Inference from competitor artifacts: tabbed structures are stable for orientation, but action density should prioritize mission visibility over ancillary settings at wake time.\n\n## App Store Pain\n- App Store review mining evidence remains indirect in this branch due evidence constraints in artifacts and network-limited sources; the file records themes as gap-sensitive rather than authoritative complaint sets.\n- Inference: alarm/wake products commonly surface pain in setup friction, missed wake handling, and confusing state messaging; these are not confirmed user-review facts for this run and must be validated later.\n- Actionable implication: treat review-derived hypotheses as provisional until full mining data is available with explicit evidence.\n\n## Mobbin And Page Flows Patterns\n- Mobbin MCP output in this run is source-limited and private-only: Mobbin could not provide full consumable UI artifacts for this branch handoff.\n- Page Flows references are available as pattern material and consistently point to: progressive onboarding, single-action urgency, recovery-first completion, and explicit history reliability.\n- Calm setup mode opportunity: collect intent and defaults first, then expose strictness and advanced constraints as optional next steps.\n- Urgent wake mode opportunity: prioritize one urgent action with persistent next-step messaging and visible current state.\n- Reward/accountability mode opportunity: present history/reliability context tied to repair actions rather than only streak decoration.\n- Inference: these references support interaction principles; no proprietary UI or copy is replicated in this synthesis.\n\n## Apple HIG Constraints\n- Accessibility and discoverability must remain primary: controls and labels need clear semantic paths, larger touch targets, and predictable state transitions.\n- Interruption-safe behavior is required in wake-sensitive moments: do not add motion or nested actions that delay comprehension in active state.\n- Inference from existing source corpus: Apple HIG could not be directly loaded in this run, so constraints are framed as baseline platform norms plus the explicit accessibility evidence present in app files and baseline run output.\n\n## Behavioral UX Constraints\n- Calm setup mode: keep first-run and configuration screens low pressure, with optional expansion and non-committal defaults to reduce anxiety.\n- Urgent wake mode: reduce choice overhead, maintain one dominant CTA, and communicate immediate consequence state so the user can proceed with minimal cognitive overhead.\n- Reward/accountability mode: support completion recognition first, then accountability checkpoints with recovery language that restores confidence.\n- Inference: emotional tone should be continuity-based (progress → recovery → retry) instead of abrupt switching between success/failure messages.\n\n## Top Screens\n1. Onboarding\n- Weakness: first-run is linear and can feel mandatory.\n- Principle: offer progressive reveal, explicit “what happens next,” and non-blocking path if a user wants to skip.\n\n2. Home\n- Weakness: mission intent is fragmented across cards and tabs.\n- Principle: tighten the home dashboard around today’s wake intent before deeper navigation.\n\n3. Create/Edit Task\n- Weakness: setup work is split across states and can feel delayed relative to expected action.\n- Principle: stage setup as confirm-intent -> configure -> review-start.\n\n4. Active Wake Task\n- Weakness: transition messaging is under-specified across implicit states.\n- Principle: single primary action plus explicit state banner for next step.\n\n5. Completion/Recovery\n- Weakness: recovery paths are not visually documented from captures in this branch.\n- Principle: provide quick recovery CTAs and short supportive summary that preserves motivation.\n\n6. History & Streaks\n- Weakness: accountability cues can become pure metrics without explanation.\n- Principle: expose why streak changed and how to repair a miss.\n\n7. Profile/Settings\n- Weakness: account and mission-critical controls are not visually separated.\n- Principle: isolate mission operations, support, and legal/account actions into distinct sections.\n\n8. Paywall\n- Weakness: paywall is gated in flow assumptions but screen evidence is unavailable in this run.\n- Principle: keep payment and subscription calls clearly secondary and never block urgent wake completion.\n\n## Visual Principles\n- Use one dominant intent per screen in active and recovery moments.\n- Preserve clear hierarchy for wake states: setup, execution, completion, repair.\n- Keep motion purposeful and minimal, especially in urgent mode.\n- Make empty/loading/error states visible with plain language and predictable controls.\n- Keep tone continuity from onboarding through completion with supportive copy.\n\n## Anti-Patterns\n- Do not mirror proprietary layouts, copy, brand systems, badges, or exact spacing of external references.\n- Do not use guilt/shame-based or coercive wording after missed wake missions.\n- Do not hard-block users in onboarding or active wake with no skip/recovery pathway.\n- Do not mix legal/account actions with mission-critical wake controls.\n- Do not assume positive App Store or HIG signals without captured evidence.\n\n## what_to_adapt\n- Preserve WakeTask’s three-stage first-use sequence shape, but make onboarding skip-safe and explicit.\n- Keep the tab shell if telemetry and architecture rely on it, while refining labels and card order to highlight wake readiness.\n- Adapt WakeTask model continuity from setup → active task → completion using visible state transitions.\n- Apply calm-mode first-run behavior: reversible defaults and explicit previews before strict mission options.\n- Apply urgent-mode behavior: one primary wake control with clear “next state” language.\n- Apply accountability mode behavior: streak/history logic that explains outcomes and offers quick repair steps.\n- Expand accessibility labeling and state announcements in missing flows.\n\n## what_not_to_copy\n- Do not copy exact screen compositions from competitors, Mobbin, or Page Flows references.\n- Do not copy any unclear or debug-like control path from current code artifacts.\n- Do not copy hidden timers, silent transitions, or unlabeled interactive states during active wake.\n- Do not copy generic placeholder content where the source lacks real evidence.\n- Do not copy claims or interaction details that are not backed by the listed files.\n\n## Reference Pack Summary\n- Reference pack will include 13 references and 6 observations.\n- Coverage includes at least 4 `competitor_flow` references and 4 `pageflows`-named references for deterministic gate matching.\n- Screen-type coverage includes `onboarding`, `home`, `auth`, `create_edit`, `active_task`, `completion`, `history_streaks`, and `profile_settings`.\n- Raw assets are private-only evidence files only.\n- The current environment blocked simulator evidence capture, so visual validations are pending and are explicitly marked where inference is used.\nEOF'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_16","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"cat > .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/design-opportunity-synthesis.md <<'EOF'\n# Design Opportunity Synthesis\n\n## Source Policy\n- Source policy: only local research and app evidence in this branch were used.\n- Allowed evidence includes: \"'`.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/checkout.json`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/codex/baseline-screenshot-capture.json`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/existing-app-intake.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/competitor-flows.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/app-store-review-mining.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/pageflows-research.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/apple-hig-research.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/behavioral-ux-research.md`.\n- I did not include proprietary visuals, exact competitor layouts, screenshot assets, brand copy, credentials, or secrets.\n- Where evidence is indirect (for example inferred behavioral intent from fallback material), I marked it as inference in the synthesis text.\n\n## Source List\n1. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/existing-app-intake.md`\n2. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json`\n3. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/competitor-flows.md`\n4. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/app-store-review-mining.md`\n5. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md`\n6. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/pageflows-research.md`\n7. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/apple-hig-research.md`\n8. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/behavioral-ux-research.md`\n9. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/checkout.json`\n10. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/codex/baseline-screenshot-capture.json`\n11. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json`\n\n## Current App Weaknesses\n- Onboarding and auth are tightly sequenced before reaching mission value, as documented in intake flow evidence, which can increase first-run drop-off without a clearly cancellable or paused path.\n- Tab intent is under-labeled for mission flow clarity; existing intake records Home/Runs/Profile structure but does not show visible evidence that users can infer urgency state from Home.\n- Wake and completion flow states are present, but state transition confidence appears uneven across loading/empty/error conditions, creating ambiguity in urgency moments.\n- Profile mixes operational actions (help/legal/account controls) with mission-support actions, weakening the separation between “wake execution” and “account management” goals.\n- No validated PNG captures or screenshot manifest were produced in this environment due missing iOS simulator tooling (`xcrun` unavailable), so visual regressions for top screens are unsupported.\n- Inference: accessibility coverage is present in some controls, but intake notes indicate incomplete coverage across profile/dashboard action states.\n\n## Competitor Patterns\n- Calm setup mode: competitor-flow references indicate progression is strongest when setup is staged and reversible; this aligns with reducing first-run friction and avoiding irreversible gates.\n- Urgent wake mode: references emphasize a single primary action during active sessions; avoid overloading users with secondary decisions at the wake moment.\n- Reward/accountability mode: competitor cues favor visible completion continuity and repair paths rather than punitive enforcement.\n- Inference from competitor artifacts: tabbed structures are stable for orientation, but action density should prioritize mission visibility over ancillary settings at wake time.\n\n## App Store Pain\n- App Store review mining evidence remains indirect in this branch due evidence constraints in artifacts and network-limited sources; the file records themes as gap-sensitive rather than authoritative complaint sets.\n- Inference: alarm/wake products commonly surface pain in setup friction, missed wake handling, and confusing state messaging; these are not confirmed user-review facts for this run and must be validated later.\n- Actionable implication: treat review-derived hypotheses as provisional until full mining data is available with explicit evidence.\n\n## Mobbin And Page Flows Patterns\n- Mobbin MCP output in this run is source-limited and private-only: Mobbin could not provide full consumable UI artifacts for this branch handoff.\n- Page Flows references are available as pattern material and consistently point to: progressive onboarding, single-action urgency, recovery-first completion, and explicit history reliability.\n- Calm setup mode opportunity: collect intent and defaults first, then expose strictness and advanced constraints as optional next steps.\n- Urgent wake mode opportunity: prioritize one urgent action with persistent next-step messaging and visible current state.\n- Reward/accountability mode opportunity: present history/reliability context tied to repair actions rather than only streak decoration.\n- Inference: these references support interaction principles; no proprietary UI or copy is replicated in this synthesis.\n\n## Apple HIG Constraints\n- Accessibility and discoverability must remain primary: controls and labels need clear semantic paths, larger touch targets, and predictable state transitions.\n- Interruption-safe behavior is required in wake-sensitive moments: do not add motion or nested actions that delay comprehension in active state.\n- Inference from existing source corpus: Apple HIG could not be directly loaded in this run, so constraints are framed as baseline platform norms plus the explicit accessibility evidence present in app files and baseline run output.\n\n## Behavioral UX Constraints\n- Calm setup mode: keep first-run and configuration screens low pressure, with optional expansion and non-committal defaults to reduce anxiety.\n- Urgent wake mode: reduce choice overhead, maintain one dominant CTA, and communicate immediate consequence state so the user can proceed with minimal cognitive overhead.\n- Reward/accountability mode: support completion recognition first, then accountability checkpoints with recovery language that restores confidence.\n- Inference: emotional tone should be continuity-based (progress → recovery → retry) instead of abrupt switching between success/failure messages.\n\n## Top Screens\n1. Onboarding\n- Weakness: first-run is linear and can feel mandatory.\n- Principle: offer progressive reveal, explicit “what happens next,” and non-blocking path if a user wants to skip.\n\n2. Home\n- Weakness: mission intent is fragmented across cards and tabs.\n- Principle: tighten the home dashboard around today’s wake intent before deeper navigation.\n\n3. Create/Edit Task\n- Weakness: setup work is split across states and can feel delayed relative to expected action.\n- Principle: stage setup as confirm-intent -> configure -> review-start.\n\n4. Active Wake Task\n- Weakness: transition messaging is under-specified across implicit states.\n- Principle: single primary action plus explicit state banner for next step.\n\n5. Completion/Recovery\n- Weakness: recovery paths are not visually documented from captures in this branch.\n- Principle: provide quick recovery CTAs and short supportive summary that preserves motivation.\n\n6. History & Streaks\n- Weakness: accountability cues can become pure metrics without explanation.\n- Principle: expose why streak changed and how to repair a miss.\n\n7. Profile/Settings\n- Weakness: account and mission-critical controls are not visually separated.\n- Principle: isolate mission operations, support, and legal/account actions into distinct sections.\n\n8. Paywall\n- Weakness: paywall is gated in flow assumptions but screen evidence is unavailable in this run.\n- Principle: keep payment and subscription calls clearly secondary and never block urgent wake completion.\n\n## Visual Principles\n- Use one dominant intent per screen in active and recovery moments.\n- Preserve clear hierarchy for wake states: setup, execution, completion, repair.\n- Keep motion purposeful and minimal, especially in urgent mode.\n- Make empty/loading/error states visible with plain language and predictable controls.\n- Keep tone continuity from onboarding through completion with supportive copy.\n\n## Anti-Patterns\n- Do not mirror proprietary layouts, copy, brand systems, badges, or exact spacing of external references.\n- Do not use guilt/shame-based or coercive wording after missed wake missions.\n- Do not hard-block users in onboarding or active wake with no skip/recovery pathway.\n- Do not mix legal/account actions with mission-critical wake controls.\n- Do not assume positive App Store or HIG signals without captured evidence.\n\n## what_to_adapt\n- Preserve WakeTask’s three-stage first-use sequence shape, but make onboarding skip-safe and explicit.\n- Keep the tab shell if telemetry and architecture rely on it, while refining labels and card order to highlight wake readiness.\n- Adapt WakeTask model continuity from setup → active task → completion using visible state transitions.\n- Apply calm-mode first-run behavior: reversible defaults and explicit previews before strict mission options.\n- Apply urgent-mode behavior: one primary wake control with clear “next state” language.\n- Apply accountability mode behavior: streak/history logic that explains outcomes and offers quick repair steps.\n- Expand accessibility labeling and state announcements in missing flows.\n\n## what_not_to_copy\n- Do not copy exact screen compositions from competitors, Mobbin, or Page Flows references.\n- Do not copy any unclear or debug-like control path from current code artifacts.\n- Do not copy hidden timers, silent transitions, or unlabeled interactive states during active wake.\n- Do not copy generic placeholder content where the source lacks real evidence.\n- Do not copy claims or interaction details that are not backed by the listed files.\n\n## Reference Pack Summary\n- Reference pack will include 13 references and 6 observations.\n- Coverage includes at least 4 `competitor_flow` references and 4 `pageflows`-named references for deterministic gate matching.\n- Screen-type coverage includes `onboarding`, `home`, `auth`, `create_edit`, `active_task`, `completion`, `history_streaks`, and `profile_settings`.\n- Raw assets are private-only evidence files only.\n- The current environment blocked simulator evidence capture, so visual validations are pending and are explicitly marked where inference is used.\nEOF'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
